04777nam a22007575i 9780823252268DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232522687 a10.1515/97808232522682doi  a(DE-B1597)555138  a(OCoLC)843882953  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aQH332b.O45 2013eb 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a174.22231 aOliver, Kelly, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTechnologies of Life and Death :bFrom Cloning to Capital Punishment /cKelly Oliver. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Moral Machines and Political Animals -- tOne. Genetic Engineering: Deconstructing Grown versus Made -- tTwo. Artificial Insemination: Deconstructing Choice versus Chance -- tThree. Girl Powered: Poetic Majesty against Sovereign Majesty -- tFour. Rearview Mirror: Art, Violence, and Sublimation -- tFive. Elephant Autopsy: Optic Machinery and the Scale of Sovereignty -- tSix. Deadly Devices: Animals, Capital Punishment, and the Scope of Sovereignty -- tSeven. Death Penalties: Ethics, Politics, and the Unconscious of Sovereignty -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe central aim of this book is to approach contemporary problems raised by technologies of life and death as ethical issues that call for a more nuanced approach than mainstream philosophy can provide. To do so, it draws on the recently published seminars of Jacques Derrida to analyze the extremes of birth and dying insofar as they are mediated by technologies of life and death. With an eye to reproductive technologies, it shows how a deconstructive approach can change the very terms of contemporary debates over technologies of life and death, from cloning to surrogate motherhood to capital punishment, particularly insofar as most current discussions assume some notion of a liberal individual.The ethical stakes in these debates are never far from political concerns such as enfranchisement, citizenship, oppression, racism, sexism, and the public policies that normalize them. Technologies of Life and Death thus provides pointers for rethinking dominant philosophical and popular assumptions about nature and nurture,chance and necessity, masculine and feminine, human and animal, and what it means to be a mother or a father. In part, the book seeks to disarticulate a tension between ethics and politics that runs through these issues in order to suggest a more ethical politics by turning the force of sovereign violence back against itself. In the end, it proposes that deconstructive ethics with a psychoanalytic supplement can provide a corrective for moral codes and political clichés that turn us into mere answering machines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBioethics. 0aBiotechnologyxMoral and ethical aspects. 4aDerrida. 4aanimals. 4aart. 4acapital punishment. 4acloning. 4agenetic engineering. 4agirls. 4areproductive technologies. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823252268zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823252268423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823252268.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  